        }
      ],
      "text": "<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"background-color:white\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><span style=\"color:#0d0d0d\">A pediatrician is conducting routine health check-ups in the outpatient department for children of various ages. While performing anthropometric measurements, a newly joined pediatric intern observes the process and later engages in a discussion about the significance and technical aspects of these measurements in assessing child health and nutritional status. The intern makes several statements about common practices in pediatric anthropometry. Which of the following statements made by the intern is NOT true regarding standard anthropometric measurements in pediatrics?</span></span></span></span></p>",
      "unique_key": "Q5757343",
